player.seasonOutlook: In what was his first season with New Jersey, the 2022-23 campaign went as well as could be reasonably expected for Vanecek. He played in 52 games, posting a 33-11-4 record, 2.45 GAA and .911 save percentage. That's the good news. The bad news is that Vanecek was downright horrific in his seven playoff appearances, sporting a ghastly 4.64 GAA and .825 save percentage while losing playing time to rookie Akira Schmid in the process. Signed for two more seasons at a cap hit of $3.4 million, Vanecek deserves the benefit of the doubt considering how well he played during the regular season, and he remains the heavy favorite to serve as New Jersey's starter throughout 2023-24. However, a team like the Devils, a legitimate Stanley Cup contender, won't hesitate to turn to Schmid if Vanecek falters.

Mrazek's first season in Chicago in 2022-23 was a bit of a train wreck on multiple fronts. He missed extended periods of time due to a groin issue, ultimately appearing just in 39 games, going 10-22-3 with career-worst marks in both GAA (3.66) and save percentage (.894). The Blackhawks improved their forward depth this offseason, starting with No. 1 overall pick Connor Bedard, but the team's defensive group remains about the worst in the NHL. That means bad news for Mrazek and his expected running mate, youngster Arvid Soderblom, in 2023-24. You should look elsewhere on draft day.

The Wild put a ton of faith in Gustavsson after acquiring him from Ottawa in July and he responded in a major way, going 22-9-7 with a sparkling 2.10 GAA and .931 save percentage while splitting time almost evenly with veteran and future Hall of Famer Marc-Andre Fleury. Set to play this entire season at age 25, Gustavsson should have the leg up for playing time considering where each netminder is at in their respective careers, but Fleury will almost certainly steal enough starts to be troublesome from a fantasy perspective. Gustavsson will have more value in leagues that allow daily lineup changes as opposed to weekly in 2023-24.

A finalist for the Vezina Trophy as the NHL's top goaltender in 2022-23, Sorokin had an exceptional year. He won 30 games for the first time in his career (31), finished tied for fifth in the league in GAA (2.33), third in save percentage (.924) and led the league in shutouts with six. He was rewarded with a well-deserved eight-year, $66 million deal in July. Semyon Varlamov was also signed to a new four-year deal to return as his backup. The only negative that can be pointed to regarding Sorokin's 2023-24 fantasy outlook is the fact he plays for a team in the Islanders that lacks offensive firepower. He projects to be one of, if not the best fantasy goaltender in 2023-24

The Hurricanes are one of the best teams in the NHL and Andersen has played well for virtually his entire career when healthy, but he's also frequently been banged-up. Last year, Andersen played just 34 games (21-11-1, 2.48 GAA, .903 save percentage), with his most notable ailment being a lower-body issue which cost him two months' worth of action from mid-November to mid-January. The two-year, $6.8 million deal he inked to return to Carolina as a free agent this offseason is a potential bargain, but the Hurricanes also re-signed Antti Raanta to a one-year deal, and they still have youngster Pyotr Kochetkov hanging around, which, combined with Andersen's lack of durability, means we are again almost certainly looking at a committee approach for the 2023-24 campaign.

The Carolina goaltending position has been a revolving door due to the fact the team's top two guys, Freddie Andersen and Antti Raanta, haven't been able to stay healthy. Kochetkov made 24 appearances in 2022-23, going 12-7-5 with a 2.44 GAA, a .909 save percentage and four shutouts. He'll play this entire season at age 24 and he's clearly the goaltender of the future for the Hurricanes, but all three men are under contract with the club for another year. Andersen is the likely starter if healthy, but Kochetkov should still see his fair share of action in 2023-224, particularly if Andersen once again misses time due to an injury.

Many believed Knight was finally primed to steal the No. 1 goaltending job from Sergei Bobrovsky in Florida last season, but it didn't work out for a variety of reasons. Knight was banged-up and didn't play well when healthy (9-8-3 record, 3.18 GAA, .901 save percentage). He entered the NHL-NHLPA Player Assistance Program in late February and didn't play again for the remainder of the season. Obviously neither the team nor the league released any details regarding a situation like that, so Knight's status heading into the upcoming season is a little murky. It's worth noting the Panthers signed Anthony Stolarz to a one-year deal to potentially serve as Bobrovsky's backup for 2023-24.

Signed to a hefty contract (three years, $14.5 million) in the summer of 2022 to serve as Detroit's new No. 1 goaltender, Husso found life in Motown playing for a rebuilding team a difficult one in 2022-23. His record was over .500 (26-22-7), but Husso's 3.11 GAA and .896 save percentage were both uninspiring and well off the marks he posted with the Blues a year prior. The Wings signed James Reimer to a one-year deal to serve as Husso's backup in 2023-24, but at age 35, Reimer isn't really a threat for extended playing time. The hope for Husso is Detroit potentially improving enough as a team to make him a serviceable No. 2 fantasy netminder this year.

Merzlikins only appeared in 30 games for the Blue Jackets in 2022-23, but there's a strong case to be made that he was the worst goaltender in the NHL when in the lineup. Playing behind a dreadful team, Elvis finished with a 7-18-2 record, 4.23 GAA and .876 save percentage. Now, Merzlikins got zero help from his teammates, but the 29-year-old Latvian has been trending in the wrong direction since his breakout 2019-20 rookie campaign. Merzlikins figures to open the 2023-24 campaign as Columbus' de-facto No. 1 goaltender, but 24-year-old Russian Daniil Tarasov is a real threat for playing time, especially if Elvis gets off to another dreadful start.

You're going to have to search long and hard to find a goaltender who had a crazier 2022-23 season than Bobrovsky. He missed significant chunks of time throughout the year, finishing with a 24-20-3 record, 3.07 GAA and .901 save percentage in 50 games. He began the playoffs as the backup to Alex Lyon, only to take over in Game 3 of Florida's first-round series against Boston. Bobrovsky proceeded to run off 11 wins in his next 13 starts along with a 2.21 GAA and a .935 save percentage, helping the Panthers to the Stanley Cup Final. The magic ended there, as Bob posted a 4.70 GAA and an .844 save percentage in the Finals against Vegas. Bobrovsky is going to open the 2023-24 campaign as Florida's starter with Anthony Stolarz backing up and Spencer Knight still in the organization. That's a potential mess from a fantasy perspective.

Fantasy managers that went back to the well with Hellebuyck following his poor 2021-22 campaign were rewarded last year. He finished with 37 wins, his highest total since the 2017-18 campaign, and Hellebuyck's 2.49 GAA and .920 save percentage were also his best marks in several years. The main question at this point is what team will Hellebuyck be playing with long term? He has one year left on his contract at a shade over $6 million and it's believed the Jets have entertained trade offers for the franchise netminder. Hellebuyck's fantasy floor should remain stable considering any team that potentially deals for him will be doing so with the intention of giving him a ton of playing time, but it's a situation to monitor throughout the season.

Shesterkin's statistics (2.48 GAA, .916 save percentage) predictably fell off from his Vezina Trophy-winning 2021-22 campaign (2.07 GAA, .935 save percentage) in 2022-23, but he still played well. He finished with a career-high 37 wins, a number that placed him tied for third in the NHL. Shesterkin is a true workhorse in a league that has very few of them left. Jonathan Quick was signed to a one-year deal to replace Jaroslav Halak as Igor's backup for the upcoming campaign. That move should have no impact on Shesterkin's fantasy value, however, as he should again play roughly 60 games and put up some of the best numbers in the NHL.

Demko's 2022-23 season was totally derailed by a groin injury which cost him the better part of three months. He ultimately appeared in 32 games, half as many as the 2021-22 campaign, and he managed just a 14-14-4 record, 3.16 GAA and .901 save percentage over that span. There have been rumblings of Demko being on the trade block, but with three years left on a contract that pays him $5 million annually, it won't be an easy deal to complete. Demko is a lock to improve on last year's numbers if he can make it through the season in one piece, but his fantasy upside for a Vancouver team that will essentially be running back the same roster is nowhere near as clear.

An unquestioned No. 1 goaltender for the first time in his NHL career, Georgiev debuted in Colorado last season following parts of five years with the Rangers and responded by winning 40 games, tying him with Boston's Linus Ullmark for most in the league. Georgiev's secondary numbers (2.53 GAA, .918 save percentage) were solid, if unspectacular. Signed for two more seasons at the bargain-bin rate of $3.4 million annually, Georgiev will return as the top guy for the Avalanche with Pavel Francouz once again backing up in 2023-24. Georgiev will remain a legitimate No. 1 fantasy option while playing for one of the NHL's top teams this year.

Ullmark won the Vezina Trophy as the NHL's top goaltender in 2022-23 despite appearing in just 49 games for the Bruins. That's what happens when you go 40-6-1 with a 1.89 GAA and .938 save percentage. He led the league in all three of those categories. How much of that is sustainable is up for debate. Jeremy Swayman is still going to get his fair share of playing time in 2023-24, and Boston will almost certainly take a step back in the standings following the loss of Patrice Bergeron, David Krejci and Taylor Hall among others in the offseason. Ullmark showed more than enough last year to be considered a no-doubt No. 1 fantasy goaltender in 2023-24, but don't pay a premium for the numbers he posted a season ago which likely won't materialize again.

Vasilevskiy didn't have a very good season by his standards in 2022-23, although most goaltenders would be elated by the numbers he posted. He won 30-plus games (34) for a sixth straight year, but his GAA (2.65) and save percentage (.915) represented his worst marks since becoming Tampa Bay's full-time starter in the 2017-18 season. In what was a huge blow to the Lightning and Vasi's outlook for 2023-24, he underwent back surgery in late September that is expected to keep him out of action for at least 8-10 weeks. That means approximately 46 starts is probably a best-case scenario for the outstanding netminder this year. Fantasy managers who are still considering the Russian backstop on draft day will need to ensure they have a fill-in option in place for the first few months of the season.

Swayman and Vezina Trophy winner Linus Ullmark essentially split time in the Boston net in 2022-23. The former appeared in 37 games, going 24-6-4 with a 2.27 GAA, .920 save percentage and four shutouts. In short, Swayman was a no-doubt No. 1 fantasy option every single time he got the call. Unable to come to terms on a long-term deal with the Bruins, Swayman took the team to arbitration and was awarded a one-year, $3.475 million contract this summer. He's going to begin the upcoming season behind Ullmark on the depth chart simply because of how dominant Ullmark was last season, but it wouldn't be surprising to see Swayman steal the lion's share of the work if Ullmark struggles.

The days of Oettinger being available at any sort of discount on draft day have come and gone on the heels of a 2022-23 season in which he finished tied for third in the league in wins (37), seventh in GAA (2.35) and tied for fourth in save percentage (.920). Oettinger appeared in 62 games last year after seeing action in no more than 48 contests over the course of his first two NHL campaigns. He faces no threat for playing time as Scott Wedgewood will once again return as the backup for the Stars, making Oettinger a top-five option at his position in fantasy leagues heading into the 2023-24 season.

The best ability is availability, and no NHL goaltender has played more than Saros in recent years. He appeared in 64 games in 2022-23, tying him with Winnipeg's Connor Hellebuyck for the league lead. Saros notched 30-plus wins (33) for a second straight season, and his GAA (2.69) and save percentage (.919) were nearly identical to his 2021-22 campaign. The Predators are an aging team trending in the wrong direction, and that may impact Saros' win total this year, but the sheer amount of starts he receives combined with his talent will keep the Finn in the conversation as a desirable No. 1 fantasy keeper in 2023-24.

No goaltender in the NHL had a wilder 2022-23 season than Hill. He began the year as the backup to youngster Logan Thompson. Thompson eventually got hurt, but Hill himself suffered a groin injury in March which cost him the better part of two months. Hill appeared in just 27 regular-season games, going 16-17-1 with a 2.49 GAA and a .914 save percentage. But it was Hill's playoff performance that will be talked about for years. He took over as the starter in Game 3 of Vegas' second-round series against Edmonton and never relinquished the net. Hill started the final 15 playoff games for the Golden Knights, posting a 2.22 GAA and a .932 save percentage in helping the team win the Stanley Cup. Hill was rewarded with a two-year, $9.8 million deal for his efforts. He and Thompson will battle for playing time in 2023-24.

Few goaltenders in the NHL are as inconsistent as Jarry. His record a season ago was fine (24-13-7), but his secondary numbers were mediocre (2.90 GAA, .909 save percentage) at best. Jarry was particularly awful late in the season when the Penguins were chasing a playoff spot, going 5-6-2 with a 3.21 GAA and an .891 save percentage in his final 15 appearances. Pittsburgh has zero interest in rebuilding with aging veterans Sidney Crosby, Evgeni Malkin and Kris Letang still under contract, and with no better option available, the Penguins handed Jarry a new five-year, $26.88 deal in free agency this summer. It could be a steal if Jarry gets his act together, but that's far from a sure thing. Casey DeSmith, who has outplayed Jarry in short spurts in the past, will return to back up.

Talbot arrived in Ottawa in 2022-23 following a couple years in Minnesota and was expected to take over as the club's No. 1 goaltender. Well, it didn't work out. Talbot was constantly banged-up and underperformed (17-14-2, 2.93 GAA, .898 save percentage) when healthy. As you might have guessed, Talbot found an ice-cold market in unrestricted free agency, ultimately having to settle for a one-year, $1 million deal with the Kings. It's a potential value signing for the club, as Talbot has played very well at times in the past, but how much playing time he'll receive in 2023-24 remains to be seen. He'll be battling fellow veteran Pheonix Copley for the starting gig.

The Flyers finished with the seventh worst record in the NHL a season ago, so it shouldn't come as a shock that Hart's numbers were once again mediocre. He posted a record below .500 (22-23-10) for a third straight year. Hart's GAA (2.94) and save percentage (.907) both improved to their best marks since his breakout 2019-20 campaign, but they were still underwhelming. Hart's name has been mentioned in trade rumors all offseason, but nothing has gotten done yet. Hart will most likely return as Philadelphia's starter with youngster Felix Sandstrom serving as the backup in 2023-24, but Hart's fantasy value will remain iffy on a team that once again projects to be one of the NHL's weakest.

The Oilers handed Jack Campbell a big contract (five years, $25 million) to take over as the team's No. 1 goaltender in 2022-23, but he struggled in a major way, paving the way for Skinner to steal the starting gig. Skinner appeared in 50 games last season, finishing with an impressive 29-14-5 record, 2.75 GAA and .913 save percentage. Skinner certainly played well more often than not, but he struggled late. In 12 playoff appearances, he had a 3.68 GAA and .883 save percan entage. He's going to begin the 2023-24 campaign as Edmonton's starter, but Campbell isn't going anywhere given his contract, so it'll be important for Skinner play well early on to keep the No. 1 job for the entire season.

A finalist for the Vezina Trophy as the NHL's top goaltender in 2021-22, Markstrom (and his teammates) took a huge step backwards in 2022-23. He managed just 23 wins compared to 37 a year prior, while his 2.92 GAA and .892 save percentage were Markstrom's worst numbers in any campaign in which he's played in at least 26 games. The 33-year-old Swede is a bounce-back candidate this year, but there's a lot of uncertainty surrounding the Flames, so it's probably wise to be cautious from a fantasy perspective.

The Maple Leafs inked Samsonov to a one-year deal last summer following Washington's surprising decision to not tender the RFA netminder. Toronto was rewarded with the best season of Samsonov's career, as he posted a 27-10-5 record, 2.33 GAA and a .919 save percentage. He missed three weeks early in the season with a knee issue and was again banged-up at the end of Toronto's playoff run, but when healthy, Samsonov performed as well as could have been reasonably expected. Unable to come to an agreement on a long-term deal, Samsonov took Toronto to arbitration this summer, ultimately being awarded with a one-year, $3.55 million contract which will take him to unrestricted free agency next summer. Despite the promising Joseph Woll set to take over as the Leafs' top backup this year, Samsonov should remain the team's No.1 netminder throughout the 2023-24 campaign, giving him ample upside in all fantasy formats.

The only good news regarding Binnington's performance from a fantasy standpoint in 2022-23 was the fact he appeared in 61 games, sixth most among NHL goaltenders. His record was just .500 (27-27-2), while Binnington's 3.31 GAA and .894 save percentage were the worst marks of his career. He was particularly bad during a 17-game stretch from mid-January to mid-March, winning just four times in 17 games. Binnington has four years left on his contract with an outlandish cap hit of $6 million annually, so it's safe to assume he's going to get his fair share of playing time in 2023-24, but with 23-year-old Joel Hofer taking over for the since-retired Thomas Greiss as the Blues' backup, it'll be imperative for Binnington to start quickly to retain the No. 1 role for the entire season.

Unhappy with the play they got from the likes of Cam Talbot, Anton Forsberg and others a season ago, the Senators handed Korpisalo a five-year, $20 million deal in free agency to serve as the club's new No. 1 goaltender in 2023-24. That contract will look like a bargain if Korpisalo can get his act together, but that's far from a given. He posted middling numbers (18-14-4 record, 2.87 GAA, .914 save percentage) a season ago in a year split between Columbus and the Kings. The 29-year-old has never played more than 39 games in a single campaign, making him a risky bet to hold up over the course of a full season. There's sneaky upside here, but it's anyone guess as to whether Korpisalo will reach it.

Kuemper signed a five-year, $26.25 deal with the Capitals in July of 2022 on the heels of leading the Avalanche to the Stanley Cup Championship. His first year with Washington did not go well. Kuemper's record was below .500 (22-26-7), while his 2.87 GAA was his worst mark since the 2016-17 season when he was the backup in Minnesota. The only real positive was the fact Kuemper had five shutouts, tying him for fourth most in the league. Washington has a new coach in Spencer Carbery, but the rest of the team's roster is essentially unchanged. That leaves Kuemper as an uninspiring fantasy option, whose greatest attribute is the fact he's locked into the No. 1 role for the Capitals.

A seventh-round pick of the Panthers acquired by the Sabres as part of the Sam Reinhart trade, Levi was the best goaltender in college hockey (38-22-6, 1.90 GAA, .942 save percentage, sixteen shutouts) over the past two years for Northeastern. He signed with Buffalo late in the 2022-23 campaign and appeared in seven of the team's final nine games, going 5-2-0 with a 2.94 GAA and a .905 save percentage. Levi is young at just 21 years old and a bit undersized (six-foot), but he's exceptional from a technical standpoint. Buffalo may start the year with some combination of Eric Comrie and Ukko-Pekka Luukkonen in goal, but it's clear as day starting Levi will give the Sabres the best chance to win hockey games.

The Ducks were one of the worst teams in NHL history in 2022-23 according to advanced defensive metrics, which makes Gibson's 14-31-8 record, 3.99 GAA and .899 save percentage completely understandable. Gibson has been an ideal change-of-scenery candidate for several years now, but Anaheim has yet to pull the trigger on a deal, which makes little sense considering Gibson is already 30 years of age and the Ducks aren't close to contending. Signed for four more seasons at a cap hit of $6.4 million, Gibson will again return as Anaheim's No. 1 goaltender with youngster Lukas Dostal backing up in 2023-24. Nonetheless, Gibson should be considered a non-factor in most fantasy circles unless he ends up getting traded.

It's a low bar, but Montembeault was the best goaltender for the Canadiens in 2022-23. He split time almost evenly with veteran Jake Allen - Montembeault appeared in 40 games last season, going 16-19-3 with a 3.42 GAA and a .901 save percentage. Montembeault had some brilliant performances, but he also gave up five or more goals on nine separate occasions. It's unlikely Montembeault is the goaltender of the future for Montreal, but he at least has some potential long-term upside, something Allen and fellow veteran newcomer Casey DeSmith don't bring to the table. He will be the favorite for regular starts when the 2023-24 campaign begins.

It's next to impossible to play any fantasy goaltender on a team as bad as Arizona, and that held true for Vejmelka in 2022-23. He appeared in at least 50 games for a second straight year, but his record was predictably terrible (18-24-6) and his supporting statistics (3.34 GAA, .899 save percentage) were even worse. Of course, that's not entirely Vejmelka's fault. The Coyotes are slowly trying to creep back toward respectability, but that doesn't mean you should use Vejmelka, who seems likely to split time with Connor Ingram in 2023-24, in your lineup. Look elsewhere on draft day.

The Kraken somehow finished with 100 points last season despite getting lousy goaltending for almost the entire year. Grubauer was so bad (17-14-4, 2.85 GAA, .895 save percentage) that he ended up playing nine fewer games (39) that Martin Jones, who was even worse (2.99 GAA, .887 save percentage). If you're looking for a positive note regarding Grubauer, he did start Seattle's final 13 playoff games. Looking ahead, Jones has moved on and Chris Driedger is expected to serve as the backup to Grubauer this year. It's difficult to see the Kraken taking a significant step forward as a team in 2023-24, meaning it's nearly impossible to see Grubauer's numbers improving significantly. He should be considered a late-round dart throw for fantasy managers looking for a depth goaltender this season.

Kahkonen played well in short spurts during his time with Minnesota from 2019-2021, but his first full season with San Jose in 2022-23 wasn't great. Kahkonen went 19-20-7 with career-worst marks in both GAA (3.85) and save percentage (.883) while splitting time with James Reimer. Kahkonen played particularly poor late in the year, posting a 4.42 GAA in his final nine appearances. His poor numbers weren't entirely Kahkonen's fault, but that's little solace to fantasy managers. Reimer is gone, and former Devil Mackenzie Blackwood has entered the fold. It's impossible to have confidence in either netminder considering the Sharks traded their best player (Erik Karlsson) this offseason and will be icing a roster that is no better and probably worse than what we saw last year.
